For practical application in food industry, the CDs were demonstrated for tri-channel detection of erythrosine in food samples, such as red wine (Fig. 4
                        ), beer (Fig. S4), blackcurrant juice (Fig. S5), and red grape juice (Fig. S6). For example, the fluorescent intensity of the CDs at 490 nm, 460 nm, and 480 nm were gradually decreased in red wine samples when the erythrosine concentrations were reduced in from 2 µM to 20 µM (Fig. 4A–C), exhibiting a linear range of 4–20 µM (Fig. 4D), 4-20 µM (Fig. 4E), and 2-20 µM (Fig. 4F) with the detection limit of 1.21 nM, 1.56 nM, and 2.05 nM, respectively. The linear ranges and detection limits for each drink were listed in Table 1
                        . The triple-channel erythrosine detection based on the CDs showed good linear range and low detection limits in all the tested drinks, although the linear ranges and detection limits varied among different drinks, indicating that it is essential to determine all these parameters for each kind of food sample.
